- §I.1 `serializeProject` shared `JsonSerializerOptions` — reused for `EnvironmentSettings` serialization (§J.6 item 1).

## Scope

This slice delivers the second Part J tranche: the [Core] persistent UI-customization & favorites board (J.6) plus the [Standard] preferences (J.7), theme & dockable panels (J.8), and input validation & physical-sanity warnings (J.9). The favorites board and the `EnvironmentSettings`/`Preferences` records are the net-new persistent customization from 010 Part II §1; preferences and panel layout/theme persist as fields of `EnvironmentSettings`. The `Validation` module is the J.9 seam that J.2 (slice 014) already calls to reject a repeat count < 1, and that the rest of the editor uses for every boundary field.

UI-touching. `EnvironmentSettings` persists as JSON validated against `optical-constructor-environment.schema.json` (NOT `.binz`), reusing the Part I `serializeProject` shared `JsonSerializerOptions` (slice 003) — not a second JSON stack. This slice relies on the slice-001 buildable FuncUI interpretation: the public MIT `Avalonia.FuncUI` NuGet supplies the DSL for compilation.

**FuncUI-clone gate for `AppShell` (J.8 / constraint 5 / §A.6 / §A.9 / AC-J8).** §J.8 states the dockable-panel mechanism MUST use Avalonia's docking facilities *through the FuncUI clone* — and therefore that the clone MUST NOT be referenced, linked, or built until the mandatory audit passes and the clone is cleared, and that the clone's linking mechanism MUST remain undecided here. `AppShell` MUST therefore be authored against the FuncUI DSL surface as SOURCE but MUST NOT add the clone as a dependency, and MUST NOT resolve the linking mechanism. The public MIT `Avalonia.FuncUI` NuGet (slice 001) supplies the DSL so `AppShell` compiles under the `build` gate; the audit-gated clone at `C:\GitHub\Avalonia.FuncUI.Clone\` stays unreferenced and its linking choice stays unresolved.

## Requirements

### R-1. §J.6 Persistent UI-customization & favorites board [Core]

The Ui project MUST provide a `UserEnvironment` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/UserEnvironment.fs`) defining an `EnvironmentSettings` record that persists the user's working environment between sessions and serves as defaults for new projects. It MUST hold: a **favorites board** (named, grouped pins of frequently used `Layer`s, `materialEntry` ids, `sourceSpec` ids, and whole sub-assemblies expressed as `OpticalSystem` fragments, all referencing §A.7 shapes), the **last working folder(s)** and an ordered **recent files/projects** list, the **window/panel layout** (J.8), the **toolbar contents**, and the **preferences** (J.7). This is the net-new persistent customization from 010 Part II §1.

1. `EnvironmentSettings` MUST be persisted as JSON validated on load against a new schema `optical-constructor-environment.schema.json` (added to the §A.7 schema family, same validation library `JsonSchema.Net` named in §A.7) — NOT as FsPickler/`.binz`, because it is hand/LLM-inspectable user config (§A.7). The serialization MUST reuse the Part I `serializeProject` shared `JsonSerializerOptions` (§I.1) rather than a second JSON stack.
2. The file MUST live at a single fixed per-user path under the OS application-data directory; the resolved path MUST be a committable-vs-gitignore non-issue because it is outside the repository working tree (J.10 checklist item 6). Sub-assemblies pinned on the favorites board MUST be stored by value as `opticalSystem` JSON fragments (§A.7), so a pinned favorite survives even if the project it came from is deleted.
3. Sweep/field-map and other bulk artefacts MUST NOT be embedded in `EnvironmentSettings`; only references (paths/ids) MAY appear, consistent with the `.binz`-sidecar rule (§A.7). Schema versioning and migration of this file are OUT OF SCOPE (§0 constraint 6); on a schema-validation failure the app MUST fall back to built-in defaults rather than attempt migration.

### R-2. §J.7 Preferences [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `Preferences` record (in `OpticalConstructor.Ui/UserEnvironment.fs`, J.6) carrying: default units (a per-quantity `unitOfMeasure`, §A.7), default wavelength range, default number of sweep points, decimal display precision, and solver defaults. Solver defaults MUST be expressed as the engine's own `SolverParameters` (`Solvers.fs:15`, whose `numberOfReflections` is the convergence control named in 010 Part II §4/§8) — Part J MUST NOT define a parallel solver-config record. Default-unit and wavelength-range preferences are display/boundary concerns and MUST be applied only at the UI/IO boundary (§A.3); they MUST NOT change how any value is stored. Preferences persist as part of `EnvironmentSettings` (J.6) and are therefore JSON, not `.binz`.

### R-3. §J.8 Theme & dockable panels [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide an `AppShell` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/AppShell.fs`) hosting dockable/resizable panels (stack, materials, sources, chart, results) with saved layouts, and a light/dark theme plus configurable chart color palettes. The theme selection and the serialized panel layout MUST be fields of `EnvironmentSettings` (J.6) and MUST round-trip through its JSON. Chart color palettes MUST be surfaced to Part H but MUST NOT be re-implemented as a charting engine here. The dockable-panel mechanism MUST use Avalonia's docking facilities through the FuncUI clone — and therefore MUST NOT be referenced, linked, or built until the mandatory FuncUI-clone audit (§A.6/§A.9 / 010 Part III §3) has passed and the clone is cleared. **The clone's linking mechanism (local NuGet package OR project reference) is deliberately undecided and MUST remain undecided here; Part J MUST NOT resolve it.** Until the audit passes, `AppShell` MUST be authored against the FuncUI DSL surface as source but MUST NOT add the clone as a dependency.

### R-4. §J.9 Input validation & physical-sanity warnings [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `Validation` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Validation.fs`) exposing pure validators returning `Result<'T, ValidationError list>` (§0 error-handling rule — `Result`, not exceptions) for every editable boundary field. It MUST enforce at minimum: thickness `> 0` for finite films (rejecting `Thickness.Thickness d` with `d <= 0.0<meter>`, `Media.fs:12`), repeat count `>= 1` (J.2), a non-empty wavelength range with positive endpoints, and the physical-sanity warnings named in 010 Part II §8 (e.g. an absorbing region flagged where the imaginary index implies gain, non-causal tabulated data). Validation MUST run at the UI boundary before a value is committed to the model and MUST surface failures inline next to the field; it MUST NOT throw, and it MUST NOT silently coerce out-of-range input. Validators MUST operate on already-parsed values and MUST NOT duplicate unit conversion — they receive canonical `double<meter>` etc. after the §A.3 boundary conversion.

## Non-requirements

- Schematic / repeat builder / templates / drag-drop / comparison workspace are Part J §J.1–J.5, owned by slice 014. J.2 calls this slice's J.9 validator; the repeat builder itself is slice 014.
- The long-running job runner, in-app help/glossary/gallery, and the 3D system/beam view are Part J §J.10–J.12, owned by slice 016. The shared job-status area in `AppShell` (J.8 item) only hosts the runner that slice 016 supplies.
- The chart color-palette IMPLEMENTATION is Part H (slice 012); J.8 only surfaces palettes to it and MUST NOT re-implement a charting engine.
- The FuncUI clone MUST NOT be referenced, linked, or built, and its linking mechanism MUST NOT be resolved (constraint 5 / §A.6 / §A.9 / AC-J8). `AppShell` is authored against the FuncUI DSL surface (public MIT NuGet, slice 001) as source only.
- Schema versioning / migration of `EnvironmentSettings` is OUT OF SCOPE; validation failure falls back to built-in defaults, never migrates (§J.6 item 3).

